  "debug_data_path": "debug_data/2020_635",
  "eprint": {
    "title": "Two-Round Oblivious Linear Evaluation from Learning with Errors",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Pedro Branco",
        "email": "pmbranco@math",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Nico Döttling",
        "email": "ptdoettling@cispa",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Paulo Mateus",
        "email": "saarlandpmat@math",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Oblivious Linear Evaluation (OLE) is the arithmetic analogue of the well-know oblivious transfer primitive. It allows a sender, holding an affine function $f(x)=a+bx$ over a finite field or ring, to let a receiver learn $f(w)$ for a $w$ of the receiver's choice. In terms of security, the sender remains oblivious of the receiver's input $w$, whereas the receiver learns nothing beyond $f(w)$ about $f$. In recent years, OLE has emerged as an essential building block to construct efficient, reusable and maliciously-secure two-party computation.\n\nIn this work, we present efficient two-round protocols for OLE over large fields based on the Learning with Errors (LWE) assumption, providing a full arithmetic generalization of the oblivious transfer protocol of Peikert, Vaikuntanathan and Waters (CRYPTO 2008). At the technical core of our work is a novel extraction technique which allows to determine if a non-trivial multiple of some vector is close to a $q$-ary lattice.",
    "keywords": [],
    "category": "Cryptographic protocols",
    "publication_info": "A minor revision of an IACR publication in PKC 2022",
    "last_updated": "2022-02-18",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
